# C. PRINTING WORDS+VARIABLES
#
# INFO: %d for decimal integers (whole numbers!)
#           %d : print using only as many spaces as needed
#          %3d : print using 3 spaces (spaces if 3 aren't needed)
#         %03d : print using 3 spaces (0-padded if 3 aren't needed)
#       %f for fractional numbers (like pi!)
#           %f : print, letting Python decide on spaces/digits
#          %6f : print, using 6 spaces
#       %c for characters (single letters)
#       %s for character strings (words)
#

# D. PRINT IN LOOP
#
# Often we print tables of values from within a loop.
# Here we'll draw an imaginary line through Hurricane Norma, above.
# We'll print out 'red' image values left-right along row 500.
#
# 1. Set NX = number of columns in Norma image above.
#    Remember "norma.shape" would give us two numbers,
#      ... the number of rows and columns.  So,
#      norma.shape[0] is the number of ROWS ... and
#      norma.shape[1] is the number of COLUMNS. Set NX = number of columns.
#
# 2. Set variable 'red' equal to the red part of our .png image.
#    Remember images are stored as [ rows, columns, colors ]
#
# 3. Start a for loop (loop variable named 'x',
#                      start at 0, stop before NX, step 40)
#      ... this range lets x go from 0 to (NX-1) at steps of 40.
#      Let's CLARIFY:
#        for n in range(10) ... has n = 0, 1, ..., 9
#        for n in range(2,12) ... has n = 2, 3, ..., 11
#        for n in range(2,20,2) ... has n = 2, 4, ..., 18
#
#    a) Inside the loop, print out x and red[500,x] .. the value at
#       row 500 and column 'x' ... so the output looks Exactly like:
#               At column x= 480, red = 0.773
#       USE 4 digits for x, and 3 after decimal point for red[].
#
# 4. PLOT Norman (1 row 2 columns):
#    a) Start a figure, dpi=150
#    b) On left, display the full color image.  Add title: Hurricane Norma
#    c) On right, plot the line of red data at row 500, meaning
#      * It's a LINE plot: use plt.plot() (not .imshow(), etc)
#      * The plot is for All columns
#      * The plot is for One row (=500)
#      * The plot is for the red channel (0, 1 or 2 ??)
#      * Also, color the line red!
#      * Add title: Red row 500
#
# Comment: Do you see the N-S longitude lines being crossed by row 500?
# They appear as spikes in the red channel ... those lines are white.

NX = norma.shape[1]
red = norma[:, :, 0]

for x in range(0, NX, 40):
    print(f'At column x = {x:4d}, red = {red[500, x]:.3f}')

fig = plt.figure(dpi=150)
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(norma)
plt.title('Hurricane Norma')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(red[500], color='r')
plt.title('Red row 500')

plt.tight_layout()

# E. HURRICANE KATRINA CONTOURS + CITY LABELS + CENTER
#
# 1. Run the code below to get and open a file and read Pres, lat, lon
#    It should work!
#
# 2. Add code to plot a US map over a blue marble image of your choosing.
#    It should contain states/provinces too.
#    Use these set_extent values:  -94, -84, 25.5, 32.5
#
# 3. Plot 20 contours of pressure (colored brown) on top of the image.
#
# 4. I give you an array of city locations. CHOOSE ANOTHER and add it --
#      ..add that city airport code, latitude, and longitude to the list.
#    You can web-search "airnav name-of-city" to find the 3-letter code.
#
# 5. Use the for-loop below. It doesn't use range(); rather, each time through,
#    the variables inside parentheses (cityname,citylat,citylon) are set to
#    the first (ID), second (latitude) and third (longitude) for that city.
#    So variables (cityname,citylat,citylon) change each time through the loop.
#
#   a) Inside the for-loop, ADD a print statement which gives output like this:
#         City TLH : latitude 30.40, longitude -84.35
#   b) Also inside the for-loop, plot the station ID (text, for each of 4 cities)
#         in white on the map at the right location.
#
# 6. Outside the loop ... Find the Eye
#    Find center of low pressure (row,col = np.where ....) and use lon, lat arrays and center
#    position row,col to plot the letter L at the pressure minimum, with fontsize=36.
#    Use this option to center the letter L:  horizontalalignment='center'
#    Hint: you're plotting at longitude lon[row,col] in ax.text().
#
# 7. One more thing! Add coastlines, using '110m'.  This isn't 110 meters, but a
#    1:110,000,000 scale, stated as "1 to 110 million". Plot it.  It looks lousy.
#    Now change it to '10m', for 1:10,000,000.  So much better.  More about
#    resolution and Natural Earth Data:  https://www.naturalearthdata.com/features/

# Given: Get/open data set, read pressure, longitude, latitude, close data set.

!wget -q -N http://rfd.atmos.uiuc.edu/305/Katrina/kat4km.nc

DS = xr.open_dataset('kat4km.nc')
pres = DS.PSFC[0, :, :] / 100  # converts Pa (pascals) to hPa (1 hPa = 1 mb)
lat  = DS.XLAT[0, :, :]       # latitude in degrees N
lon  = DS.XLONG[0, :, :]      # longitude in degrees E
DS.close()
print('Pressure values range from %.2f to %.2f millibars' % (np.min(pres), np.max(pres)))

# Start figure, plot a map, add states
!wget -q -N https://neo.gsfc.nasa.gov/archive/bluemarble/bmng/world_2km/world.200411.3x21600x10800.jpg
from PIL import Image
Image.MAX_IMAGE_PIXELS = None
world2km = np.array(Image.open('world.200411.3x21600x10800.jpg'), dtype=np.uint8)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
ax = plt.axes(projection=ccrs.PlateCarree())
ax.imshow(world2km, origin='upper', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(), extent=[-180, 180, -90, 90])
ax.set_extent([-94, -84, 25.5, 32.5], crs=ccrs.PlateCarree())
ax.add_feature(cfeature.STATES.with_scale('10m'))

# Plot twenty pressure contours (contour() chooses the 20 values)
ax.contour(lon, lat, pres, 20, colors='brown', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree())

# City list:
cities = [["MSY",29.99,-90.26],
          ["TLH",30.40,-84.35],
          ["MOB",30.69,-88.24],
          ["PNS",30.47,-87.19]]

# Show cities!  Your print() statement goes here.
for (cityname, citylat, citylon) in cities:
    ax.scatter(citylon, citylat, color='white', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree())
    ax.text(citylon, citylat + 0.3, cityname, color='white', transform=ccrs.PlateCarree())
    print(f'City {cityname} : latitude {citylat}, longitude {citylon}')

# Show center as L (low pressure)
row, col = np.where(pres == np.min(pres))
ax.text(lon[row, col], lat[row, col], 'L', fontsize=36, horizontalalignment='center', color='white')

# Add coastlines
ax.add_feature(cfeature.COASTLINE.with_scale('10m'))
plt.title('KATRINAAAA')
plt.tight_layout()

Pressure values range from 925.51 to 1005.15 millibars

City TLH : latitude 30.4, longitude -84.35
City MOB : latitude 30.69, longitude -88.24
City PNS : latitude 30.47, longitude -87.19
